#heading(numbering: none, outlined: false)[Abstract]

Danish food-safety inspections produce a public smiley grade that updates only at the inspector's next visit, leaving Fødevarestyrelsen with no early signal for restaurants whose hygiene deteriorates between scheduled visits. We ask whether Google Maps reviews can fill that gap. Earlier US Yelp work reported classification accuracies of 78%–90%+, but the only full-register replication found the signal was largely explained by prior inspection history, and the Danish setting has not been tested. 

From 6,000 register entries matched to Google Maps places and filtered to food-service establishments, we built a per-visit panel of 8,067 inspections across 2,957 restaurants at a 14.9% non-happy rate. Review coverage is uneven: 34% of inspection windows contain no reviews, and the median non-empty window holds twelve reviews. Each inspection is paired with the reviews written between the previous inspection and the visit, so the features mirror what an inspector could have seen in advance. We summarised each window with three features (log review count, mean star rating, share of low-star reviews) and added a six-category hygiene-flag layer scored per review by a locally hosted Gemma 4B classifier with a Danish prompt. Logistic regression and XGBoost were fit to the three-class smiley target under 5-fold place-grouped stratified cross-validation with restaurant-clustered bootstrap intervals.

The three summary features raised not-happy PR-AUC from a 0.149 class-frequency baseline to 0.182 (95% CI 0.169 to 0.197) and top-decile precision from 0.149 to 0.201, a 35% relative gain. The hygiene flags added nothing on top, every per-class PR-AUC interval overlapped the summary-only configuration, and eleven of twelve adjusted odds ratios included 1, with the only exception on the food-safety-concern flag for the sad-vs-happy contrast. We read this as a modest lift from the summary features and a null result for the LLM hygiene flags, and we do not recommend deployment based on this work.     A full-history register slice, keeping every inspection per restaurant rather than only the four most recent, would help determine whether the observed lift is real or mainly an artefact of the four-slot cap. Whether it would substantially improve predictive performance is less clear, however, since the current design also faces other constraints, including sparse review coverage outside larger cities, noisy or fake reviews, and a target variable that mixes diner-observable and diner-invisible hygiene failures into the same smiley grade.
